\f0 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 The context\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf4 \cb3 \strokec5 Britain\'92s trading relationships with the world are a key component of its foreign policy, providing an\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 opportunity to boost economic growth at home while promoting British values and interests abroad. Yet as\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 we approach the next general election, global trade faces a set of unprecedented challenges.\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 The outbreak of Covid-19 sent shockwaves across the international economic system, and global supply\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 chains have struggled to recover from the disruption of national lockdowns, including the dramatic\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 contraction and subsequent resurgence in demand for goods and services. This is not something that\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 has been and gone; many countries continue to deal with outbreaks of the virus in 2023.\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 Meanwhile, Russia\'92s illegal invasion of Ukraine has led to soaring energy costs across Europe and driven\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 a global food crisis. Manufacturing costs have increased and household budgets have been squeezed,\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 placing signi\uc0\u64257 cant strain on the everyday lives of working people.\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 In Britain, the challenges of global trade have been exacerbated by almost 13 years of Conservative\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 mismanagement, recklessness and neglect.\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 Having overseen our withdrawal from the European Union, the Conservative government failed to deliver\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 on the trade promises they made, with the UK economy left paying the price. Instead of prioritising exports,\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 growth and jobs across the UK, or taking a lead on using trade to tackle the climate crisis and workers\'92\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 rights, Conservatives simply cut and paste pre-existing deals that were negotiated decades ago.\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 In their 2019 manifesto, the Conservatives promised that 80 per cent of Britain\'92s trade would be covered\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 by free trade agreements by the end of 2022, yet they have now missed their own deadline.\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 This failure to deliver on trade targets is incredibly damaging, leaving the UK economy missing out on billions\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 of pounds of potential opportunities that could boost growth here in the UK.\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 Boris Johnson and Liz Truss repeatedly promised new trade deals with India and the US, but these are yet\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 to materialise.\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 Out of the few trade deals that have been signed, almost all have fallen short. Instead of aiming for\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 ambitious new trade deals with international partners, the Conservatives have rushed around in search of\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 the quickest agreements they can \uc0\u64257 nd, with no questions asked.\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 The Australian trade deal failed to include binding commitments on climate targets and risks undercutting\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 UK farmers through the removal of import tari\uc0\u64256 s. By the Conservatives\'92 own admission,\cf0 \cb1 \
