\f4\i \cf4 \cb3 \strokec5 \'93the UK gave away\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 far too much for far too little in return\'94\cf0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\i0 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec5 \'a0when negotiating the Australia deal.\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 In its negotiations with the EU, the Government\'92s antagonistic approach repeatedly undermined progress\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 and soured key relationships, limiting any chance of a new kind of progressive agreement. The last minute\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 deal was far from what was promised, with signi\uc0\u64257 cant gaps that make trading with European partners much\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 more burdensome than before..\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 Moving into 2023, the Northern Ireland Protocol impasse remains one of the most damming examples of the\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 Conservatives\'92 failure on the international stage, with progress remaining slow. In government, Labour must\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 immediately get to work on securing a better deal for British people.\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 After 13 years of Conservative government, Britain\'92s reputation as a reliable and trusted partner has\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 been signi\uc0\u64257 cantly damaged. On trade, it is clear the Conservatives have no strategy, which is costing jobs,\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 investment and growth. Labour knows that Britain deserves better.\cf0 \cb1 \
