\f0 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 The future under Labour\'a0\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf4 \cb3 \strokec5 In light of our withdrawal from the EU, Britain will need to develop a bespoke and \uc0\u64258 exible trade policy that is\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 \uc0\u64257 t for the future.\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 Negotiating an independent trading policy will be a signi\uc0\u64257 cant challenge for a future Labour government.\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 It will fall to Labour to grow the UK\'92s economy and show that Britain can once again be a force for good on\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 the international stage.\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 Heading into the next election, it is clear that Labour is the party of economic growth. The Labour Party\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 has already set out a clear plan to make Britain and its people better o\uc0\u64256 , giving the country the fresh start\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 it needs.\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 International trade will be a vital part of this, helping deliver jobs at home while promoting Britain\'92s principles\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 abroad. From defending workers\'92 rights to tackling the climate crisis, the Labour Party has the opportunity to\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 develop a comprehensive trade policy that puts Labour values into action.\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 Building on the commission\'92s previous consultation, where the NPF looked at the importance of promoting\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 Labour\'92s internationalist values through multilateral alliances, promoting aid and bolstering democratic\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 systems, the commission will this year look to develop the party\'92s position on trade.\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 The starting point must be the restoration of Britain\'92s reputation as a trusted partner, both to our closest\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 neighbours in Europe and our allies further a\uc0\u64257 eld. Labour has already outlined plans to scrap the treaty-\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 breaking Protocol Bill and deliver real progress to ease trade, key \uc0\u64257 rst steps in building a new working\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 relationship with Europe and solving the Northern Ireland issue.\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 The Labour Party will make Brexit work outside of the single market and the customs union, helping to move\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 the country on from the arguments and divisions of the past. The veterinary agreement Labour will seek with\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 the EU would eliminate most checks in agricultural goods, but there is much more to do.\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 Labour will seek to use trade policy to boost the economy and promote jobs, to create a trading\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 environment that works for Britain. The UK is home to some of the best and most innovative businesses in\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 the world, but they need the right platform to thrive. Labour\'92s international trade policy must support this,\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 particularly for businesses who rely on global supply chains.\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 Importantly, Labour understands that the bene\uc0\u64257 ts of trade must be felt across the whole of the UK.\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 The country simply cannot go on with a situation where just 1.4 per cent of exports are from the North\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 East and less than 5 per cent of exports originate from the East Midlands, compared to 25 per cent from\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 London and 21 per cent from the South East.\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 The recent Commission on the UK\'92s Future chaired by Gordon Brown highlighted this disparity,\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 recommending a bigger role for devolved leaders as one way of tackling regional inequality.\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 Labour is keen to build on this, and is looking at how a Labour government can further open up\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 services and use trade to help level up across our regions and nations.\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 Following the recent disruption of the global pandemic and the war in Ukraine, Labour must consider what\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 lessons to learn about the resilience of international trade to global events and use trade policy to better\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 secure the UK\'92s supply chains. This could include working closer with allies and partners to strengthen the\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 international trading system.\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 To tackle the climate crisis and seize the economic opportunities of decarbonisation, Labour has set out\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 plans to drive green British exports. At Annual Conference 2022, Shadow International Trade Secretary Nick\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 Thomas-Symonds explained how a new network of Climate Export Hubs will work with businesses, universities\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 and other innovators to take UK climate science innovations and export them to the world. These export\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf4 \cb3 hubs will support every region in the country \'96 helping to create skilled jobs and opportunities nationwide.\cf0 \cb1 \
